    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-01-24T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-01-24T23:00:00-05:00" n="472"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d472">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1111 <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1"
                        >Baker, Charles</persName>/7: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hankow (<persName
                            corresp="frus1932v03#p_AWA1" type="from">Adams</persName>) to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-01-25T12:00:00+08:00"
                            >January 25, 1932—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received January 25—8
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>16. My number 14, January 23, noon.<note n="5" xml:id="d472fn5">Not
                        printed.</note> The bandits who hold <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1"
                        >Baker</persName> state that the price of his ransom “will be decided upon
                    by the Hupeh Soviet government” and will be communicated to messenger at
                    Pailochi on January 28th.</p>
                <p>The comprador of the Yangtze Rapid lighter No. 2 is coming to Hankow to give
                    details of the capture of <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1"
                        >Baker</persName> to General <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_HC1">Ho
                        Chen-chun</persName>, Chairman of the Hupeh Provincial Government.</p>
                <p>The President of the Yangtze Rapid Steamship Company has expressed a willingness
                    to pay a maximum of silver dollars 10,000 for <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s release. He thinks, however,
                    that the Chinese authorities should pay the sum demanded for <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s ransom.</p>
                <p>Legation and Nanking informed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_AWA1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Adams</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
